 >> Anonymous Sat Aug 15 12:28:36 2020 No.12011231 >>12011117The roots of s^2+2.ω0.ζ.s+ω0^2=0 are s=-ω0.ζ±ω0√(ζ^2-1). In the time domain, x(t)=a1.e^(s1.t)+a2.e^(s2.t) where s1, s2 are the roots.If ζ=0 (undamped), then s=±i.ω0; in the time domain, this is a constant-amplitude sinusoidal oscillation.If |ζ|=1 (critically damped), then s=-ω0.ζ, a duplicate root which is real and negative. In the time domain, this is a.t.e^(-ω0.t).If |ζ|<1 (underdamped), √(ζ^2-1) is imaginary so the roots form a complex conjugate pair; in the time domain, you have (e^-ηt).cos(ωt+φ), i.e. an exponentially-decaying sinusoid.If |ζ|>1 (underdamped), √(ζ^2-1) is real and you have two distinct real roots, meaning exponential decay in the time domain.
